ce:section.ce:para:
It is evident from the characterization of the polymerization process that PDs were formed from the precursor OPD molecules by stirring at room temperature for 3 days. From the PL spectra at the different stirring times (
Figure S1
), it can be observed that the PL intensity around 560 nm gradually increases up to the maximum and stabilizes (absolute PLQY of 2.86%) at 3 days, thus 3 days was chosen as the reaction time. From the TEM image ( Figure S2
), the quasi-spherical particles appear well distributed and have an average size of 29.6 nm. More importantly, these particles don’t have any crystal lattice, suggesting the formation of polymeric structure PDs rather than CPDs.[11] To provide more proof, the polymer features of as-prepared PDs were further identified by thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) and the derivative thermogravimetric analysis (DTG). As shown by Figure S3 , PDs exhibited only one weight loss process before 200 °C and the final residue is close to zero. Such a one-step decomposition process is a typical characteristic of single-component polymers such as polystyrene and polyethylene or poly (methyl acrylate). [11,14,15] It indicates the observed quasi-spherical particles only compose polymer chains without a carbon core. Additionally, XPS was used to quantitate the chemical compositions changes from OPD molecules to PDs. From Figure S4 , the full XPS spectrum showed three typical peaks at 285.0, 399.0, and 532.0 eV, respectively, indicating that PDs mainly consisted of C, N, and O. [16,17] The high-resolution spectra revealed the chemical bonds of CC/CC, CN, CO, COC, and CO in the C1s spectra and O1s spectra.[18] Moreover, the N1s spectrum can be divided into three peaks at 398.5, 399.4, and 401.4 eV, which were assigned to pyridinic N, amino N, and graphitic N, respectively.[10,19,20] The possible chemical structure of PDs is shown in Figure S5 in the supporting information. Since there are no pyridinic N, and graphitic N in the reactant (OPD), the aforementioned XPS results confirm the formation of PDs by polymerization of OPD molecules. In addition, Table S1 in the supporting information shows the solubility of PDs in various solvents, and the results show relatively higher solubility of PDs in DMSO, DMF, THF, and acetone than that in n-hexane, toluene, ether, and ethanol. By using PDs dispersing in THF, the number-average molecular weight (Mn) and weight-average molecular weight (Mw) of PDs were determined as 13,282 and 30,187 by GPC. Obviously, the large molecular weight of PDs also confirms the occurrence of polymerization between OPD molecules.
